remarks.example:
The following example demonstrates typical usage:

// Get a service instance
var service = serviceLocator.GetService<IMyService>();

// Try to get a service (safe for optional dependencies)
if (serviceLocator.TryGetService<IOptionalService>(out var optionalService))
{
    optionalService.DoSomething();
}

// Create a scope for scoped services
using (var scope = serviceLocator.CreateScope())
{
    var scopedService = scope.GetService<IScopedService>();
}

remarks.para:
It is the caller's responsibility to dispose of the returned scope when it is no
longer needed. The recommended pattern is to use a  statement:

using (var scope = serviceLocator.CreateScope())
{
    var scopedService = scope.GetService<IScopedService>();
    // Use scopedService...
} // Scope and scoped services are disposed here

remarks.example:
The following example demonstrates typical service registration patterns:

// Register a service with its implementation and lifetime
registry.Register<IMyService, MyServiceImpl>(ServiceLifetime.Scoped);

// Register a singleton instance
registry.RegisterSingleton<IMySingleton>(new MySingleton());

// Register using a factory method
registry.Register<IFactoryService>(locator => 
    new FactoryService(locator.GetService<IDependency>()), 
    ServiceLifetime.Transient);

// Check if a service is already registered
if (!registry.IsRegistered<IMyService>())
{
    registry.Register<IMyService, DefaultImpl>(ServiceLifetime.Singleton);
}

Creating and using a service locator:

var collection = new ServiceCollection();
collection.Register<IMyService, MyServiceImpl>(ServiceLifetime.Singleton);
collection.Register<IDependency, DependencyImpl>(ServiceLifetime.Transient);

using (var locator = new ServiceLocator(collection))
{
    var service = locator.GetService<IMyService>();
    // Use service...
}
